<subSubSection id="FA905881FFF42E2426C7FC4EFB95FDD2" pageId="7" pageNumber="272" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="B2350B0AFFF42E2426C7FC4EFB95FDD2" blockId="7.[151,1437,259,1186]" pageId="7" pageNumber="272">
<emphasis id="80FED718FFF42E2426C7FC4EFEEAFE8A" bold="true" box="[199,322,331,357]" pageId="7" pageNumber="272">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
This species can be recognized by the following combination of characters: mandibles with three teeth (
<figureCitation id="2AB1178FFFF42E2426DEFC6AFE9EFE66" box="[222,310,367,393]" captionStart="FIGURE 4" captionStartId="7.[151,250,1951,1975]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,1209,1926]" captionTargetId="figure-457@7.[151,1436,1209,1927]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="FIGURE 4. Details of Forrestopius nasutus, sp. nov. A. Habitus of female, in lateral view (scale bar = 2 mm) B. Head and pronotum, in lateral view C. Facial view D. Head and mesosoma, in dorsal view. E. Mandibles." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5531255" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5531255/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="272">Fig. 4E</figureCitation>
), labrum exposed when the mandibles are closed, clypeus strongly swollen with a nose-like prominence (
<figureCitation id="2AB1178FFFF42E2426EAFC96FEECFE42" box="[234,324,403,429]" captionStart="FIGURE 4" captionStartId="7.[151,250,1951,1975]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,1209,1926]" captionTargetId="figure-457@7.[151,1436,1209,1927]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="FIGURE 4. Details of Forrestopius nasutus, sp. nov. A. Habitus of female, in lateral view (scale bar = 2 mm) B. Head and pronotum, in lateral view C. Facial view D. Head and mesosoma, in dorsal view. E. Mandibles." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5531255" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5531255/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="272">Fig. 4B</figureCitation>
), with lower part concave (
<figureCitation id="2AB1178FFFF42E24247FFC96FD71FE42" box="[639,729,403,429]" captionStart="FIGURE 4" captionStartId="7.[151,250,1951,1975]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,1209,1926]" captionTargetId="figure-457@7.[151,1436,1209,1927]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="FIGURE 4. Details of Forrestopius nasutus, sp. nov. A. Habitus of female, in lateral view (scale bar = 2 mm) B. Head and pronotum, in lateral view C. Facial view D. Head and mesosoma, in dorsal view. E. Mandibles." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5531255" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5531255/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="272">Fig. 4C</figureCitation>
), face transversely striate (Fig, 4C), antenna with 30 flagellomeres, pronotum with a short wrinkle arising from pronotal pit reaching less than one third of way to anterior margin, body with intense blue to purple reflections. This species looks similar to 
<taxonomicName id="758A7089FFF42E242206FCD9FBC5FE1A" authorityName="Gauld &amp; Sithole" authorityYear="2002" box="[1030,1133,475,501]" class="Insecta" family="Ichneumonidae" genus="Forrestopius" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="272" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="judyae">
<emphasis id="80FED718FFF42E242206FCD9FBC5FE1A" box="[1030,1133,475,501]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="272">F. judyae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, both have mandibles with three teeth, head subquadrate behind ocellar triangle, vertex long and almost flat, and occiput abruptly declivous. 
<taxonomicName id="758A7089FFF42E242388FF05FF45FDD2" authorityName="Alvarado &amp; Palacio" authorityYear="2021" class="Insecta" family="Ichneumonidae" genus="Forrestopius" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="272" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="nasutus">
<emphasis id="80FED718FFF42E242388FF05FF45FDD2" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="272">F. nasutus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
can be differentiated by having the clypeus nasute and the exposed labrum.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="FA905881FFF42E2B26C7FF42FE28FE66" lastPageId="8" lastPageNumber="273" pageId="7" pageNumber="272" type="description">
<paragraph id="B2350B0AFFF42E2426C7FF42FC4EFD8E" blockId="7.[151,1437,259,1186]" box="[199,998,583,610]" pageId="7" pageNumber="272">
<emphasis id="80FED718FFF42E2426C7FF42FE68FD8E" bold="true" box="[199,448,583,609]" pageId="7" pageNumber="272">Description. Female:</emphasis>
Body length 
<quantity id="7572A6EFFFF42E242458FF42FD17FD8D" box="[600,703,583,610]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.39" pageId="7" pageNumber="272" unit="mm" value="13.9">13.9 mm</quantity>
. Fore wing length 9.0mm.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="B2350B0AFFF42E2426C7FF6EFC2BFC6E" blockId="7.[151,1437,259,1186]" pageId="7" pageNumber="272">
<emphasis id="80FED718FFF42E2426C7FF6EFEA3FD6A" box="[199,267,619,645]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="272">Head.</emphasis>
Face and clypeus 0.7× as long as wide, face transversely striate (
<figureCitation id="2AB1178FFFF42E2425F6FF6EFBE7FD6A" box="[1014,1103,619,645]" captionStart="FIGURE 4" captionStartId="7.[151,250,1951,1975]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,1209,1926]" captionTargetId="figure-457@7.[151,1436,1209,1927]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="FIGURE 4. Details of Forrestopius nasutus, sp. nov. A. Habitus of female, in lateral view (scale bar = 2 mm) B. Head and pronotum, in lateral view C. Facial view D. Head and mesosoma, in dorsal view. E. Mandibles." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5531255" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5531255/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="272">Fig. 4C</figureCitation>
), centrally granulate, clypeus strongly swollen with a nose-like prominence, clearly differentiated from face (
<figureCitation id="2AB1178FFFF42E24220AFF8AFBCAFD46" box="[1034,1122,655,681]" captionStart="FIGURE 4" captionStartId="7.[151,250,1951,1975]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,1209,1926]" captionTargetId="figure-457@7.[151,1436,1209,1927]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="FIGURE 4. Details of Forrestopius nasutus, sp. nov. A. Habitus of female, in lateral view (scale bar = 2 mm) B. Head and pronotum, in lateral view C. Facial view D. Head and mesosoma, in dorsal view. E. Mandibles." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5531255" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5531255/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="272">Fig. 4B</figureCitation>
), sparsely punctate dorsally, ventrally concave and granulate with transverse wrinkles centrally; labrum exposed when mandibles are closed; mandibles stout, with three teeth (
<figureCitation id="2AB1178FFFF42E24240EFFD2FDCDFD1E" box="[526,613,727,753]" captionStart="FIGURE 4" captionStartId="7.[151,250,1951,1975]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,1209,1926]" captionTargetId="figure-457@7.[151,1436,1209,1927]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="FIGURE 4. Details of Forrestopius nasutus, sp. nov. A. Habitus of female, in lateral view (scale bar = 2 mm) B. Head and pronotum, in lateral view C. Facial view D. Head and mesosoma, in dorsal view. E. Mandibles." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5531255" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5531255/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="272">Fig. 4E</figureCitation>
); malar space 0.4× as long as basal mandibular width; lateral ocellus separated from compound eye by about 2.0× maximum ocellar diameter; distance between ocelli 1.0× maximum ocellar diameter; vertex behind ocellar triangle almost flat, occiput abruptly declivous far back; gena in lateral view about 2.2× as long as compound eye; antenna with 30 flagellomeres, ratio of length from second to fourth flagellomeres: 1.0:0.9:0.8, subapical flagellomere 0.8× as long as centrally broad.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="B2350B0AFFF42E2426C7FE89FD4CFB4D" blockId="7.[151,1437,259,1186]" pageId="7" pageNumber="272">
<taxonomicName id="758A7089FFF42E2426C7FE89FE97FC4A" box="[199,319,908,933]" class="Crustacea (awaiting allocation)" family="Crustacea (awaiting allocation)" genus="Mesosoma" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Crustacea (awaiting allocation)" pageId="7" pageNumber="272" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="80FED718FFF42E2426C7FE89FE97FC4A" box="[199,319,908,933]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="272">Mesosoma</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. Pronotum with a short wrinkle arising from pronotal pit reaching less than one third of way to anterior margin (
<figureCitation id="2AB1178FFFF42E24273AFEAAFE3AFC26" box="[314,402,943,969]" captionStart="FIGURE 4" captionStartId="7.[151,250,1951,1975]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,1209,1926]" captionTargetId="figure-457@7.[151,1436,1209,1927]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="FIGURE 4. Details of Forrestopius nasutus, sp. nov. A. Habitus of female, in lateral view (scale bar = 2 mm) B. Head and pronotum, in lateral view C. Facial view D. Head and mesosoma, in dorsal view. E. Mandibles." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5531255" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5531255/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="272">Fig. 4B</figureCitation>
); metapleuron smooth and polished with sparse setae over its entire surface; submetapleural carina smooth, anteriorly expanded into a punctate triangular lobe. Propodeum with lateromedian longitudinal carina strong, slightly closer to each other anteriorly (
<figureCitation id="2AB1178FFFF42E2424D1FEF2FC83FBFE" box="[721,811,1015,1041]" captionStart="FIGURE 4" captionStartId="7.[151,250,1951,1975]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,1209,1926]" captionTargetId="figure-457@7.[151,1436,1209,1927]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="FIGURE 4. Details of Forrestopius nasutus, sp. nov. A. Habitus of female, in lateral view (scale bar = 2 mm) B. Head and pronotum, in lateral view C. Facial view D. Head and mesosoma, in dorsal view. E. Mandibles." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5531255" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5531255/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="272">Fig. 4D</figureCitation>
); area basalis+superomedia 3.6× as long as wide; lateral longitudinal carina complete; posterior transverse carina complete, enclosing area petiolaris and area coxalis. Fore wing with vein 
